{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2011}} {{Use Australian English|date=August 2011}} {{refimprove|date=April 2018}} {{Infobox court case | name = Bond v The Queen | court = [[High Court of Australia]] | image = Coat of Arms of Australia.svg | date decided = 14 August 1992 | full name = Bond v The Queen | citations = {{cite AustLII|HCA|13|2000|parallelcite=(2000)&nbsp;201[[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]]&nbsp;213; 169&nbsp;[[Australian Law Reports|ALR]]&nbsp;607}} | judges = [[Murray Gleeson|Gleeson]] [[Chief Justice of Australia|CJ]], [[Mary Gaudron|Gaudron]], [[Michael McHugh (judge)|McHugh]], [[William Gummow|Gummow]], [[Michael Kirby (judge)|Kirby]], [[Kenneth Hayne|Hayne]] [[Justices|JJ]] | prior actions=''The Queen v Bond'' (1997) 24 [[Australian Corporations and Securities Reports|ACSR]] 518; (1997) 95 A Crim R 246 | appealed from = [[Supreme Court of Western Australia|WA Court of Criminal Appeal]] | subsequent actions = | opinions = '''(6:0)''' The authority contained in s17 of the ''Director of Public Prosecutions Act 1983'' (Cth) did not give the Commonwealth DPP the power to institute appeals in state courts. <small> (per curiam)</small>
'''(6:0)''' The common law principles relating to the validity of acts done by an invalidly appointed public officer had no application. <small> (per curiam)</small>}}
'''''Bond v The Queen''''',<ref name="Bond v The Queen">{{cite AustLII|HCA|13|2000|litigants=Bond v The Queen |parallelcite=(2000) 201 [[Commonwealth Law Reports|CLR]] 213; (2000) 169 [[Australian Law Reports|ALR]] 607}}.</ref> was a significant case decided in the [[High Court of Australia]] regarding the power of the Commonwealth [[Director of Public Prosecutions|DPP]] to institute appeals in state courts.
== Background == Alan Bond had pleaded guilty in the [[Supreme Court of Western Australia]] to 2 charges of failing to act honestly in his capacity as an officer of a company, with intent to defraud the company and its shareholders. He was sentenced to a total 4 years imprisonment. The [[Director of Public Prosecutions (Australia)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] appealed his sentence to the Court of Criminal Appeal, of which the court allowed the appeal and sentenced Alan Bond to 7 years imprisonment.<ref name="Bond v The Queen"/>
Alan Bond appealed to the High Court on the grounds that the [[Director of Public Prosecutions (Australia)|Director of Public Prosecutions]] didn't have the authority to appeal the sentence imposed on him.
